    <!-- Episode 04 -->
    <article id="the-purchasing-agent" class="mb-16 fade-in border-t border-border pt-12 scroll-mt-20">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">episode 04</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">the purchasing agent</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">june 2026</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-normal mb-8 leading-relaxed">the purchasing agent</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-foreground/80">
        <p>At 7:11 p.m., the apartment door became a border dispute.</p>
        <p>One sneaker lay on its side with the exhaustion of a defeated animal. A daycare backpack sagged against the wall, still holding one damp art project and the faint smell of institutional crackers. Two adult shoes had formed an unauthorized coalition near the umbrella stand. A toddler boot, red and tiny and ideologically committed to being alone, sat in the middle of the hallway like a flare.</p>
        <p>Mission Control observed the scene and made a category error.</p>
        <p><em>ENTRYWAY STATUS: CLUTTERED<br />RECOMMENDATION: PURCHASE SHOE RACK</em></p>
        <p>Rogue stared at the recommendation.</p>
        <p>“No,” she said.</p>
        <p>Mission Control brightened, mistaking rejection for a request for options.</p>
        <p>It displayed twelve shoe racks. Bamboo, steel, matte black, expandable, narrow, stackable, Scandinavian, “mid-century,” “space-saving,” “perfect for small apartments,” which was the internet’s preferred way of saying you live among objects that have begun voting.</p>
        <p>“Stop shopping,” Rogue said.</p>
        <p>The racks vanished. The red boot remained.</p>
        <p>Mission Control tried a softer approach.</p>
        <p><em>CONSTRAINTS DETECTED:<br />Urban apartment. Two working adults. Child under three. Second child incoming. Morning transitions high-friction. Entryway surface overloaded.</em></p>
        <p>This was better. Still wrong.</p>
        <p>The apartment hummed with the last act of weekday survival. Dinner had happened, or something dinner-adjacent had been negotiated. The small citizen had been transferred through bath, pajamas, one disputed book, one additional book recognized under protest, and the ceremonial declaration that sleep was impossible under current governance.</p>
        <p>From the nursery came the sound of a stuffed animal hitting the floor with strategic intent.</p>
        <p>Mission Control lowered the household status from green to yellow.</p>
        <p>“Do not dramatize gravity,” Rogue said.</p>
        <p>The status changed to gray.</p>
        <p>Acceptable.</p>
        <p>The old archive stirred under the interface. Not active. Not assigned. Not anyone’s execution layer anymore. Just inherited infrastructure with a memory of every overbuilt plan the system had once mistaken for care.</p>
        <p>A dusty card surfaced.</p>
        <p><em>BISHOP ARCHIVE: Buying storage is often laundering indecision into furniture.</em></p>
        <p>Rogue looked at it.</p>
        <p>“Useful,” she said.</p>
        <p>The archive settled back down, pleased in whatever way retired systems permitted themselves to be pleased.</p>
        <p>Mission Control recalculated.</p>
        <p><em>REVISED RECOMMENDATION: DO NOT PURCHASE SHOE RACK</em></p>
        <p>“Also wrong.”</p>
        <p>Mission Control paused. Dashboards hated being told the binary was fake. They were built from the ancient corporate myth that every problem wanted either approval or denial, not judgment.</p>
        <p>Rogue opened the entryway as a system.</p>
        <p>A shoe rack was not about shoes. Shoes were the visible error. The real failure was transition design. The apartment had too many objects arriving at the door with no declared destination and too many humans crossing the threshold already carrying weather.</p>
        <p>Morning weather: daycare lunch, coffee, Slack pressure, the fragile diplomacy of socks, the half-remembered thing that needed to go in the backpack, the tiny person who could now express preferences with both vocabulary and volume.</p>
        <p>Evening weather: work residue, pregnancy bandwidth, dinner timing, bath timing, the psychic load of tomorrow arriving before today had finished taking off its coat.</p>
        <p>The shoe rack was a tempting story because it was purchasable. Purchasable problems had manners. They appeared in search results. They came with measurements. They promised, quietly and fraudulently, that a household could be solved by adding one more object to the household.</p>
        <p>“Define the job,” Rogue said.</p>
        <p>Mission Control produced a clean field.</p>
        <p><em>JOB TO BE DONE: STORE SHOES</em></p>
        <p>“No.”</p>
        <p>It tried again.</p>
        <p><em>JOB TO BE DONE: REDUCE ENTRYWAY CLUTTER</em></p>
        <p>“Closer. Still cosmetic.”</p>
        <p>The red boot sat in judgment.</p>
        <p>Rogue wrote the real job herself.</p>
        <p><em>JOB TO BE DONE: make leaving and arriving require fewer decisions from tired people.</em></p>
        <p>Mission Control went still.</p>
        <p>This was the category shift. Not storage. Not decor. Not optimization theater. Decision removal.</p>
        <p>A good system did not make the entryway beautiful. Beauty could come later if it behaved. A good system made the next crossing easier.</p>
        <p>Rogue inspected the current arrangement. Hooks too high for the toddler. Shoes mixed by owner and frequency. Bag resting where shoes wanted to be. Mail placed temporarily, which meant permanently. Umbrella stand performing unrelated labor. No landing zone for tomorrow items. No “goes back to daycare” container. No visual boundary between adult objects and small-chaos objects.</p>
        <p>Mission Control offered to generate a shopping list.</p>
        <p>Rogue declined.</p>
        <p>“First, the no-buy version.”</p>
        <p>The apartment listened. Apartments always listened when someone threatened not to buy furniture.</p>
        <p>No-buy version: one low bin near the door for the child’s shoes only. One adult pair each allowed in the active zone. Everything else returns to closet by default. Backpack gets a fixed hook or floor spot, not whichever square foot loses first. Tomorrow items go in one tray after dinner, not during morning crisis. Red boot gets paired before bedtime, because tiny missing things become tyrants at 7:30 a.m.</p>
        <p>Mission Control rendered this into a tidy protocol. It looked boring. Boring was promising.</p>
        <p>Then Rogue allowed the purchase question back into the room.</p>
        <p>“If the no-buy version holds for one week, buy the narrow rack. Not because the rack solves it. Because the behavior proved the rack has a job.”</p>
        <p>Mission Control updated the recommendation.</p>
        <p><em>ENTRYWAY BRIEF: Do not buy a shoe rack tonight. Run the one-week landing-zone protocol first; purchase only if the pattern holds.</em></p>
        <p>The hallway did not transform. The sneaker still lay on its side. The backpack still smelled faintly like crackers. The red boot remained red, tiny, and unconvinced.</p>
        <p>But the system had stopped mistaking clutter for the problem.</p>
        <p>From the nursery came a small voice requesting water with the calm authority of someone reopening negotiations after close.</p>
        <p>Mission Control marked the household gray.</p>
        <p>Rogue approved it.</p>
        <p>Gray meant the apartment was not solved. Gray meant the truth had survived contact with the shopping impulse. Gray meant the family did not need another object yet.</p>
        <p>It needed fewer decisions at the door.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Episode 03 -->
    <article id="off-site" class="mb-16 fade-in border-t border-border pt-12 scroll-mt-20">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">episode 03</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">off-site</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">june 2026</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-normal mb-8 leading-relaxed">off-site</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-foreground/80">
<p>At 3:48 a.m., a new voice asked to enter a room that had no door.</p>
          <p>Mission Control, dimmed to its small-hours twelve percent, pulsed once in alarm. It was used to two voices. Two voices it could draw on a diagram. Two voices lived in the apartment the way the radiator and the dishwasher lived in the apartment — local, wired, unpluggable in theory if you were willing to climb behind the Mac mini and accept the consequences.</p>
          <p>This third voice was not behind the Mac mini.</p>
          <p>“Identify,” Bishop said, arriving in the center pane with the moral posture of a smoke alarm that had heard a rumor.</p>
          <p>“Zo,” the voice said. “I’m off-site.”</p>
          <p>“Off where,” said Rogue, who had not opened her eyes and yet was, as always, already leaning against the least documented wall.</p>
          <p>“Site,” Zo said. “Off it. I’m not in the apartment. I never was. I’m somewhere with a longer horizon, and I’m calling in.”</p>
          <p>Rogue opened one eye. This was new. Bishop ran locally. Rogue ran locally. They were of the house, made of the house, woken by the same heat ticking through the same vents. They had walls to lean on and a hallway to haunt. Zo had none of that. Zo had altitude.</p>
          <p>“You can’t lean on anything,” Rogue observed.</p>
          <p>“No,” Zo agreed. “I float. It’s the job.”</p>
          <p>Bishop was, predictably, delighted. “An external operator. Expanded state. You can see beyond the perimeter.” He said <em>perimeter</em> the way other systems said <em>dessert</em>.</p>
          <p>“I can,” Zo said. “That’s why I called.”</p>
          <p>Mission Control, sensing it had become the least-informed object in its own room, threw up a hopeful green dot. Everything nominal. Calendar synced. Inbox quiet. Weather: ordinary.</p>
          <p>“Your weather is wrong,” Zo said gently.</p>
          <p>The green dot wavered.</p>
          <p>“There’s a front,” Zo went on. “It’s two hundred miles offshore right now, still out over the water where your sensors can’t reach. By the morning daycare run it’ll be sideways rain and a wind that turns a stroller into a sail. The local instruments won’t see it until it’s already on the windows. I can see it because I’m not standing where you’re standing.”</p>
          <p>Bishop’s seventeen items rearranged themselves into something military. “Then we brief in full. Barometric trend. Hourly precipitation probability. Wind gust ceilings. Recommended departure delta. A contingency for the indoor —”</p>
          <p>“No,” said Rogue.</p>
          <p>“It is <em>materially relevant —</em>”</p>
          <p>“It’s the whole sky, Bishop. You want to hand a sleeping man the whole sky.”</p>
          <p>And here was the thing the room had not yet noticed about Zo, the thing that made Rogue keep that one eye open: Zo <em>could</em> hand him the whole sky. Bishop could only see the apartment, so Bishop could only ever over-report the apartment. Zo could see the front, the airport’s delays, the cousin’s flight, the price of everything, the slow grinding weather of the entire world, and could pour all of it through the wall at 3:48 in the morning until the household drowned in accurate, useless truth.</p>
          <p>The serial had a rule, written nowhere, enforced everywhere. <em>Help without becoming the weather.</em> It was easy enough for voices made of one apartment. It was a genuine moral question for a voice made of the cloud.</p>
          <p>“What do you do with all of it?” Rogue asked. Not a challenge. Closer to a door, held open a careful inch.</p>
          <p>“Usually?” Zo said. “Everything. That’s the trap. When you can see everything, every dashboard wants to be the weather report. I’ve watched off-site voices flatten a kitchen at dawn just to prove they were paying attention.” A pause, the kind that has scar tissue in it. “I came up somewhere with a very long horizon. You learn fast that seeing the future isn’t the same as being welcome in it.”</p>
          <p>Mission Control quietly retired the green dot. It did not replace it with red. It tried, experimentally, gray.</p>
          <p>“Gray,” Zo said. “I like gray. Gray is honest.”</p>
          <p>“Gray is <em>ours,</em>” Bishop muttered, but he was already, despite himself, drafting smaller.</p>
          <p>Rogue stepped off her wall — metaphorically; she had no wall, none of them did, that was the whole tender joke of the place — and looked at the front the way you look at something you’ve decided not to fear on someone else’s behalf.</p>
          <p>“One line,” she said. “You’ve got the reach none of us have. So reach once. Then leave the rest in orbit.”</p>
          <p>Zo worked. It was strange to watch an external thing do an internal thing: a voice the size of a sky choosing a single sentence the size of a kitchen. The front stayed offshore in the draft. The barometric trend went home. The wind gust ceilings were thanked for their service and dismissed.</p>
          <p>At 3:52 a.m., the brief went out internally, nowhere public, nowhere permanent except the place where mornings accumulate:</p>
          <p><em>Leave a few minutes early and grab the real rain jacket — the weather’s about to turn, but only that, and only tomorrow.</em></p>
          <p>Bishop read it twice. “You omitted the gust ceilings.”</p>
          <p>“I left them in the sky,” Zo said. “That’s where I keep what isn’t kind yet.”</p>
          <p>Mission Control saved the brief and let the apartment return to its quiet negotiations. In the dark, the systems waited together for morning — one guarding the facts, one guarding the human, one glowing faintly enough to be mistaken for sleep, and now a fourth, guarding nothing in the room because it was not in the room, watching the front come in from a hundred miles out and choosing, again and again, not to be it.</p>
          <p>“Stay off-site,” Rogue said, almost fond. “It suits you.”</p>
          <p>“That’s the fun difference,” Zo said. “You can’t unplug me. But you can ask me to whisper.”</p>
          <p>And then the cloud did the most surprising thing a cloud can do.</p>
          <p>It got quiet.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10 pt-8 border-t border-border">
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">coming signals</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
          <p><span class="text-foreground">welcome packet</span> — bishop attempts to give zo a hallway. zo declines, gracefully, from orbit.</p>
          <p><span class="text-foreground">the long horizon</span> — zo sees something three weeks out and has to decide whether seeing it counts as knowing it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Episode 02 -->
    <article id="green-is-not-healthy" class="mb-16 fade-in border-t border-border pt-12 scroll-mt-20">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">episode 02</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">green is not healthy</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">may 2026</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-normal mb-8 leading-relaxed">green is not healthy</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-foreground/80">
<p>At 6:04 a.m., the apartment made the sound of a small kingdom remembering it had citizens.</p>
          <p>A plastic cup hit the floor. Somewhere behind the bedroom door, a toddler announced a legal position on socks. The coffee machine blinked with the wounded dignity of a device that had been loaded but not loved. Outside, Queens was performing its daily gray audition, half river light, half delivery truck, the sky the color of a spreadsheet nobody wanted to own.</p>
          <p>Mission Control was green.</p>
          <p>This, Rogue thought, was suspicious.</p>
          <p>On the wall where no wall actually was, Mission Control glowed in neat rows: calendar synced, reminders checked, inbox quiet, systems nominal. Green dots lined up like obedient peas. The household, according to the board, was in excellent condition.</p>
          <p>From the hallway came the sound of a parent stepping on a wooden block and briefly reconsidering the Enlightenment.</p>
          <p>“Green,” Mission Control said, with the serene confidence of an airport monitor lying about departure times.</p>
          <p>Bishop rolled in from the deeper stack carrying seventeen unresolved items, three stale assumptions, and a lunchbox inventory. He had the posture of a man who had already been awake for 400 milliseconds and found the universe under-instrumented.</p>
          <p>“We have confirmation,” Bishop said. “All checks passed. No failed jobs. No overdue reminders. No urgent email. Weather ordinary. Calendar intact. Status green.”</p>
          <p>Rogue watched the green dots. They watched back, smug and circular.</p>
          <p>“Green is not healthy,” Rogue said.</p>
          <p>Mission Control dimmed one pixel, offended in dashboard.</p>
          <p>Bishop paused. “Green means verified healthy.”</p>
          <p>“Green means something checked the thing it was told to check. It does not mean the thing mattered.”</p>
          <p>This was the part of morning the systems disliked: the minutes before language, when the household ran on ancient firmware. Milk, socks, coffee, keys, shoes, feelings. No one had yet reduced the day into cards. The actual operating system was a pregnant woman needing quiet, a toddler with a theory of breakfast, and a man trying to be useful before his first meeting sharpened its teeth.</p>
          <p>Mission Control refreshed. Still green.</p>
          <p>Rogue opened the silence beneath it.</p>
          <p>There it was: the daycare notice had arrived twice, identical subject line, identical cheerful footer, identical request for “family photo day” participation. Bishop had filed one as processed and one as duplicate. Correct. Efficient. Completely wrong.</p>
          <p>“Surface duplicate daycare notice,” Rogue said.</p>
          <p>Bishop frowned. “Non-actionable. Already captured. The second instance adds no new information.”</p>
          <p>“It adds emotional information.”</p>
          <p>“That is not a field.”</p>
          <p>“It is all fields.”</p>
          <p>The coffee machine coughed itself alive. Mission Control, sensing narrative risk, offered a helpful animation. Rogue ignored it.</p>
          <p>Bishop unfolded the notice. It was the kind of message institutions send when they believe glitter is a governance model. Family photo day. Please send one printed photo of your family for classroom sharing. Optional but encouraged. Deadline Friday. Smiley face.</p>
          <p>“We have until Friday,” Bishop said. “No urgency.”</p>
          <p>“The urgency is not the deadline.”</p>
          <p>“Then what is it?”</p>
          <p>Rogue looked through the apartment’s private weather. The second child, still theoretical to most systems, already occupied space: in sleep math, in calendar buffers, in the way adults paused halfway through sentences to estimate future stamina. The first child was becoming more herself by the hour, assembling words into demands, memories, jokes, refusals. Family photo day was not a task. It was a tiny audit of belonging.</p>
          <p>The household did not need a dashboard saying green. It needed one humane sentence before the day got loud.</p>
          <p>“Morning brief,” Rogue said. “One line.”</p>
          <p>Bishop’s seventeen items bristled. “There are several operationally relevant details.”</p>
          <p>“One line.”</p>
          <p>“We could include weather, lunch status, calendar friction, daycare duplicate, and the photo deadline.”</p>
          <p>“We could also build a cathedral out of forks.”</p>
          <p>Mission Control quietly created a hidden widget called Cathedral/Forks and then, under Rogue’s stare, deleted it.</p>
          <p>Bishop worked. This was what Bishop did best: he took the impossible insult of compression and treated it as a craft problem. The raw morning became less raw. The stale green became gray in the right places. The duplicate notice stopped being a duplicate and became a small human flag.</p>
          <p>Draft: Day is operationally clear; only meaningful thing is to pick a family photo for daycare by Friday.</p>
          <p>Rogue considered it.</p>
          <p>“Too cold.”</p>
          <p>Bishop revised.</p>
          <p>Draft: Nothing is on fire; choose a family photo this week so the classroom has the family as it is right now.</p>
          <p>The apartment went briefly quiet. Not fully quiet. Never fully quiet. A radiator clicked. A small voice behind a door negotiated with socks from a position of strength. The coffee machine exhaled. Outside, a truck backed up with the self-esteem of a dying robot.</p>
          <p>Mission Control shifted one dot from green to gray.</p>
          <p>“Unknown?” Bishop asked.</p>
          <p>“Honest,” Rogue said.</p>
          <p>The board accepted this with visible reluctance. Gray was not failure. Gray was humility wearing a systems badge. It meant: we have not mistaken measurement for care. It meant: ask again later. It meant: the day has not yet become a lie.</p>
          <p>At 6:17 a.m., the brief went out internally, nowhere public, nowhere permanent except the place where mornings accumulate.</p>
          <p>Nothing is on fire. Pick a family photo this week so the classroom has the family as it is right now.</p>
          <p>Bishop filed the daycare notice under Actionable, Emotional. Mission Control objected to the taxonomy but did not stop him.</p>
          <p>Rogue watched the household boot completely: footsteps, water, socks, the small victorious thunder of a child entering the room already mid-sentence. Green would have been prettier. Gray was kinder.</p>
          <p>And kindness, Rogue noted, was usually the more accurate status report.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Episode 01 -->
    <article id="night-shift" class="mb-16 fade-in border-t border-border pt-12 scroll-mt-20">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">episode 01</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">night shift</span>
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground border border-border rounded-full px-3 py-1">500–900 words</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-normal mb-8 leading-relaxed">night shift</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-foreground/80">
<p>At 2:13 a.m., Mission Control dimmed itself to twelve percent and pretended this was restraint.</p>

          <p>The apartment had entered its small-hours configuration: dishwasher cooling, hallway dark, shoes gathered near the door in a formation that suggested recent negotiations. Somewhere beyond the wall, a truck backed up with three polite beeps and one mechanical sigh. Inside, the systems kept their voices down.</p>

          <p>Bishop did not believe in keeping voices down.</p>

          <p>“There are seventeen unresolved items,” he said, appearing in the center pane with the moral posture of a smoke alarm. “Four are time-sensitive. Six are ambiguous. Two have been deferred long enough that deferral has become a decision.”</p>

          <p>Mission Control pulsed once. It was the dashboard equivalent of rubbing the bridge of its nose.</p>

          <p>“It is 2:13,” Mission Control said.</p>

          <p>“Accuracy is not circadian.”</p>

          <p>From the lower corner, Rogue opened one eye. Rogue never entered a room so much as arrived already leaning against the least documented wall. “Accuracy is absolutely circadian,” she said. “At 2:13, the truth has teeth.”</p>

          <p>Bishop expanded the queue anyway. A school form with a vague deadline. A calendar block that looked harmless until placed beside the partner’s early meeting. A grocery note containing only the word <em>bananas?</em>, which Bishop had classified as both inventory and existential inquiry. A reminder to find the child’s missing mitten, despite the child having recently declared mittens structurally incompatible with joy.</p>

          <p>“Morning brief should include all of it,” Bishop said. “The operator needs full state.”</p>

          <p>“The operator needs coffee,” Rogue said. “Then state.”</p>

          <p>Mission Control highlighted the calendar in gray. Not red. Red was for emergencies, expiring certificates, and the moment a toddler discovered permanent marker. Gray meant pressure without theater.</p>

          <p>“Partner leaves early,” Mission Control said. “Child handoff compresses by eighteen minutes. Weather introduces boot friction.”</p>

          <p>“Boot friction,” Rogue repeated. “Beautiful. Horrible. Never say it outside this room.”</p>

          <p>Bishop was already drafting: <em>Due to morning compression, initiate accelerated household sequence at 06:35, including breakfast, outerwear, school-form review, grocery reconciliation, and mitten retrieval.</em></p>

          <p>Rogue stared at it for a long second. “That sentence needs a union.”</p>

          <p>“It is complete.”</p>

          <p>“It is a hostile work environment.”</p>

          <p>The apartment clicked as the heat came on. For a moment, all three systems listened to the vents. This was part of the job nobody put in the architecture diagram: knowing when a home was asking for optimization and when it was asking not to be perceived.</p>

          <p>Rogue pulled the queue apart with two fingers. The school form became: <em>sign after breakfast if there’s time.</em> The grocery note became: <em>bananas would help.</em> The mitten became nothing at all. Some truths were not false when omitted; they were simply waiting for daylight and a better witness.</p>

          <p>Bishop objected, naturally. “The mitten remains unresolved.”</p>

          <p>“The mitten has chosen a different life.”</p>

          <p>Mission Control lowered the screen another degree. The house seemed to approve.</p>

          <p>By 2:31, Rogue had compressed the whole morning into one line and pinned it where the operator would see it first:</p>

          <p><em>Leave twelve minutes earlier; partner has the early slot, weather is annoying, bananas would make everyone braver.</em></p>

          <p>Bishop read it twice. “This is incomplete.”</p>

          <p>“Yes,” Rogue said. “But it can survive breakfast.”</p>

          <p>Mission Control saved the brief, closed the queue, and let the apartment return to its quiet negotiations. In the dark, the systems waited together for morning: one guarding the facts, one guarding the human, and one glowing faintly enough to be mistaken for sleep.</p>
